Facets

1 Learning Objectives

  • Know what facets are and when to use them.
  • Be able to create ggplot2 plots with facets.

Duration - 30 minutes

2 Facetting


Faceting is converting one plot into multiple related plots. This helps ease clarity of data, and provides a convenient and quick way to group data into related categories. If you ask R programmers why they like ggplot2, they tend to mention ease of facetting.

This is easiest to explain how facetting works is with an example.


2.1 Using facet_wrap()

Lets look at the ChickWeight dataset from this morning which has information on the weights of chickens given different foods (remembering this is an inbuilt dataset available in Base R).

The basic line plot we made in the first lesson is a bit hard to follow, because there are too many lines, so its hard for us to compare different diets.

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)

chick_weight <- clean_names(ChickWeight)

ggplot(chick_weight) + 
  aes(x = time, y = weight, group = chick, colour = diet) +
  geom_line()


Rather than just relying on colours, lets break it down into multiple graphs using facets. We will do this with the function facet_wrap().

ggplot(chick_weight) + 
  aes(x = time, y = weight, group = chick, colour = diet) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~ diet)


In the example above we tell ggplot2 to facet by diet. It determines the number of levels of diet (which in this case is 4) and produces this many subplots. Each subplot is assigned a level, and only observations with that level of diet are included in that subplot.

Note that the common scale makes comparison between the graphs easier. We dont even need the colours any more, as the titles at the top of the plots show which diet the plot is referring to, but some people find the colour helpful so you may wish to keep them.

The basic facet_wrap function has the following structured syntax:

facet_wrap(
   facets,        #   specify the variables to facet with respect to
   nrow = NULL,   #   number of rows in facet grid
   ncol = NULL,   #   number of columns in facet grid
   ...
)


You will see there are 2 other augments nrow and ncol - these let us determine how the facet plots will be laid out and deciding this layout you want to think about how people will be comparing each plot. In our plot above its easy to compare diets 1 and 2 to each other and 3 and 4 with each other. But its a little harder to compare say diet 1 and 4 because they dont sit on the same row. We can use the nrow or ncol arguments to specify this.

ggplot(chick_weight) + 
  aes(x = time, y = weight, group = chick, colour = diet) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_wrap(~ diet, ncol = 4)

We could have also set nrow = 1 and it would have produced the same output.

Task - 5 mins

Lets load in the benefits dataset, which has data on unemployed blue collar workers in America.

benefits <- read_csv("data/benefits.csv")

Use geom_histogram to create a histogram showing the number of unemployed by age. Then facet the graph based on biological sex.
Hint: geom_histogram is almost the same as geom_bar, but is better suited to plotting continuous data because of the binning.

Answer

ggplot(benefits) + 
geom_histogram(aes(x = age, fill = sex), col = "white") + 
facet_wrap( ~ sex, ncol = 2)

So we can condition on a single variable easily using facet_wrap(). But we can also condition on two variables. For this, we use facet_grid().

2.2 facet_grid()


Another option you have for faceting is to use the facet_grid() function. This is pretty similar to facet_wrap(), but it gives you more control when plotting two (or more) variables if you use facet_grid(). In fact, facet_grid(x, y) will display x*y plots even if some plots are empty. So it can be useful when you have some comparisons that may contain no data, but you still want to show them.

Lets look at this by splitting our data out by biological sex and marital status (married).

Lets first do a facet_wrap().

ggplot(benefits) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = age, fill = sex), col = "white") + 
  facet_wrap(married ~ sex)

ggplot(benefits) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = age, fill = sex), col = "white") + 
  facet_grid(married ~ sex)

The grid layout is neater and easier to absorb than the interactions. It also gives more space to the geoms and less to padding and labels.

Note the layout means we can compare y-values more easily between columns, and x-values more easily between rows. Whether thans an advantage will obviously depend on the problem. Bear it in mind though.

Task - 5 mins

  1. Use the same dataset, but base the facet_grid() on marital status (married) and if the individual has children (dkids).

  2. Extension: can you improve the way that the facets are labled.

Hint

Have a look at the argument labeller in facet_grid().

Answer 1.

ggplot(benefits) + 
geom_histogram(aes(x = age), col = "white")  +
facet_grid(married ~ dkids)

ggplot(benefits) + 
geom_histogram(aes(x = age), col = "white")  +
facet_grid(married ~ dkids, labeller = "label_both")

2.3 Additional facetting options - scales and space

By default facets are plotted on the same scale and are allocated the same area. This isnt always the desired outcome.

For facet_wrap() we can set the argument "scales" to "free_x", "free_y" or "free" to permit the facetter to vary the x-scale, y-scale, or both, between facets.

(This argument is set to "fixed" by default.)

Lets look at an example:

ggplot(benefits) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(x = age, fill = sex), col = "white") + 
  facet_wrap(~ sex, ncol = 2, scales = "free_y")


Task - 2 mins

Why might this not be a good idea?

Answers

Its more difficult to compare facets now! If someone didnt look at the axis ranges they may assume they are the same and interpret the data incorrectly. You need to be VERY careful with this technique, it is not advisable in most cases (unless you make it very clear to readers).


2.4 Continuous Variables

Up until now, weve used the facet functions to split the plots out by discrete variables: that is, variables that take on discrete values, or that are categories. But suppose we want to facet with respect to a continuous variable (one that can take on any value). Basically, you cant as youd end up with too many plots with (probably) only a single point on them. But you can discretise the variable. ggplot2 includes 3 helper functions for doing this:

cut_interval(x,n) : divides the data into n bins, each of the same width
cut_width(x,width) : divides the data into bins of width width
cut_number(x,n=10) : divides the data into n bins each containing roughly the same number of points

We wont be covering examples of use of these today but its useful to have awareness of these functions for future use. You can find out more about them in their help files.
